    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Ancient Roman inns that served cooked delicacies and full meals, usually having a narrow, long floor plan with serving boys attending and the proprieter sitting at one end. Cauponae were relatively low-class establishments, distinguished from the better class "tabernae meritoriae."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
